'''Memphis Depay''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈmɛɱfɪz dəˈpɑi}}; born 13 February 1994), commonly known simply as '''Memphis''',<ref name=things/> is a Dutch professional footballer who plays as a forward for [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] in the [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]]. He is the [[List of international goals scored by Memphis Depay|all-time top scorer]] for the national team with 55 goals.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 September 2025 |title=51: Memphis in zijn eentje topscorer aller tijden van Oranje|url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/51-memphis-in-zijn-eentje-topscorer-aller-tijden-van-oranje |access-date=7 September 2025 |website=Voetbal International}}</ref> In addition to his football career, Memphis is also a musician.

Memphis began his professional career with [[PSV Eindhoven]], where, under the influence of manager [[Phillip Cocu]], he became an integral part of the team, scoring 49 goals in 124 games across all competitions. During the [[2014–15 Eredivisie#Top scorers|2014–15 season]], he was the [[Eredivisie]]'s top scorer with 22 goals in 30 games, and helped the team win the Eredivisie title for the first time since 2008. He also won the [[Dutch Footballer of the Year#Dutch Football Talent of the Year|Dutch Footballer of the Year]] for his performances during the season. His performances also led him to be named the "Best Young Player" in the world in 2015 by ''[[France Football]]''. Memphis joined English side [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in June 2015 for a reported fee of £25 million. After a disappointing spell there, he joined French club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] in January 2017. Following five seasons in France, Memphis joined [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on a free transfer in 2021, where he won [[2022–23 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2023 Supercopa de España|Supercopa de España]] in his second season, although he also transferred to [[Atlético Madrid]] in the first quarter of 2023. Following his departure from Atlético at the end of the 2023–24 season, Memphis joined Brazilian side Corinthians in September 2024, winning the [[2025 Copa do Brasil|Copa do Brasil]] in 2025.

A product of the [[Royal Dutch Football Association]] (KNVB) institution, Memphis has represented the national team at every professional level from early developmental stages under the tutelage of iconic Dutch coaches and players alike. He was part of the [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands under-17 team]] which won the [[2011 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2011 European Championship]]. He made his senior debut in 2013 and the following year was part of their squad that came third at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], where he made his breakthrough performances on the international stage. He also took part in [[UEFA Euro 2020]], the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].
{{TOC limit}}

==Early life==
Memphis Depay was born in the small [[South Holland]] village of [[Moordrecht]] to a Ghanaian father, Dennis Depay, and a Dutch mother, Cora Schensema.<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last=Ramesh |first=Priya |date=8 July 2015 |title=Manchester United's Memphis Depay: the dream chaser who defied the odds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/jul/08/manchester-united-memphis-depay-dream-chaser |access-date=17 July 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> It was not long, however, before the relationship between the two parents began to fall apart and when Memphis was four, his father walked out on the family.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/memphis-depay-s-father-pleads-with-son-to-end-17year-rift-and-denies-abandoning-him-10489543.html |title=Memphis Depay's father pleads with son to end 17-year rift and denies abandoning him |last=Orr |first=James |date=7 September 2015 |work=The Independent |accessdate=23 May 2022}}</ref>

Since 2012, Memphis has dropped his last name to sever ties with his father: as he has remarked earlier, "Do not call me Depay, call me Memphis."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2021/06/19/60ce2bac22601d76568b463b.html |title=Memphis explains why he prefers not to be called Depay |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|MARCA]] |first=M. Carmen |last=Torres |date=19 June 2021 |access-date=13 August 2021}}</ref>

==Club career==
===PSV Eindhoven===
Memphis impressed football scouts from [[Sparta Rotterdam]] at the age of eight on the fields of his boyhood club Moordrecht. It took only three seasons before scouts from Sparta snatched Memphis from his local club. Club chairman Ton Redegeld said, "Memphis was as a young player already complete. He was two-footed and strong. If we won 7–0, he scored five times and would assist two times".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Residents Moordrecht pride in "their" Memphis Depay: "We lived intensely with him ' |url=http://www.omroepbrabant.nl/?news/2291961183/Amateurclub+Depay+krijgt+geen+cent+na+megatransfer+Wij+moeten+het+hebben+van+een+broodje+Memphis.aspx |website=Omroep Brabant |access-date=13 August 2016}}</ref> When he turned 12, Memphis caught the eye of clubs such as [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[PSV Eindhoven]] and [[Feyenoord]]. His grandfather, despite being an Ajax fan himself, advised Memphis to move to PSV.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="bbc">{{cite news |date=7 May 2015 |title=Memphis Depay: Who is Man Utd's new £30m forward? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32627853 |access-date=9 May 2015 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref>

====2011–13: Beginnings====
[[File:Depay PSV 2011.jpg|thumb|upright|Memphis with PSV Eindhoven in 2011|left]]
In 2011, Memphis was on trial for PSV's first team while playing for [[Jong PSV]], the club's reserve team. He made his official debut on 21 September 2011 in a [[2011–12 KNVB Cup|KNVB Cup second round match]] against amateur side [[VVSB]], opening an 8–0 away win.<ref>{{cite web |title=VVSB VS. PSV 0 – 8 |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2011/09/21/netherlands/knvb-beker/voetbal-vereniging-sint-bavo/psv-nv/1136009/ |publisher=Soccerway|access-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> His first Eredivisie match was 26 February 2012, when PSV beat rivals Feyenoord 3–2{{Citation needed|reason=seems like a ludicrously lopsided score line...check for vandalism?|date=March 2018}} at the [[Philips Stadion]], coming on in added time for [[Zakaria Labyad]]. On 18 March, six minutes after replacing [[Dries Mertens]], he scored his first league goal to confirm a 5–1 win over [[SC Heerenveen|Heerenveen]]. He made a total of eight league appearances in his first season, all as a substitute, scoring three goals.

Memphis featured in the 2012 [[Royal Dutch Football Association|KNVB]] Cup Final on 8 April, playing the final four minutes of the 3–0 win over [[Heracles Almelo|Heracles]] in place of Mertens at [[De Kuip]] in [[Rotterdam]] under interim coach [[Phillip Cocu]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cocu maakt Depay lid van de PSV selectie |url=http://psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Cocu-maakt-Depay-lid-van-de-PSVselectie.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715015834/http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Cocu-maakt-Depay-lid-van-de-PSVselectie.htm |archive-date=15 July 2012 |access-date=23 July 2012 |website=PSV |language=nl}}</ref> On 29 June, Memphis signed his first professional contract with PSV, tying himself to the ''Boeren'' until 2017.<ref>{{cite web |date=29 June 2012 |title=Contractverlenging voor Memphis Depay |url=http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Contractverlenging-voor-Memphis-Depay.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102134700/http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Contractverlenging-voor-Memphis-Depay.htm |archive-date=2 November 2013 |access-date=24 June 2014 |publisher=PSV |language=nl}}</ref> On 5 August, Memphis featured in the [[2012 Johan Cruyff Shield]] at the [[Amsterdam Arena]], replacing [[Luciano Narsingh]] for the final six minutes as PSV defeated league champions Ajax 4–2. He made 20 Eredivisie appearances in his second season, scoring twice, including two starts. The first of these was on 2 March 2013 in a 2–0 home win over [[VVV-Venlo]], scoring after three minutes after being set up by fellow teenager [[Jürgen Locadia]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=McVitie |title=Eredivisie Round 25 Results: PSV stay top while Ajax beat Twente |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/match/psv-vs-vvv/1290640/report |work=Goal.com |date=2 March 2013 |access-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> PSV again reached the cup final, losing 1–2 to [[AZ Alkmaar]] on 9 May, with Memphis playing five minutes in place of Mertens.

[[File:Memphis Depay 2012.jpg|180px|thumb|right|Memphis with PSV Eindhoven in 2012]]

====2013–14: Breakthrough season====
Memphis scored his first goal in UEFA competition on 30 July 2013, when he drifted in from the left and then smashed the ball into the top corner past goalkeeper [[Sammy Bossut]] as PSV defeated [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]] 2–0 in the first leg of their [[2013–14 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#First leg 3|UEFA Champions League]] third qualifying round tie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/020b-0e857fecf2a2-d9d3a5a8d051-1000--depay-stunner-puts-psv-on-course-to-advance/ |title=Depay stunner puts PSV on course to advance |publisher=UEFA |date=30 July 2013 |access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref> PSV failed to qualify for the group stage of the [[2013–14 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0257-0def32b1ad03-50c458fa7aad-1000--boateng-double-helps-milan-power-past-psv/ |title=Boateng double helps Milan power past PSV |publisher=UEFA |date=28 August 2013 |access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref> but in its second group stage match in the [[2013–14 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], Memphis scored again in a 2–0 win against [[FC Chornomorets Odesa|Chornomorets Odesa]] on 3 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/020e-0e86a9dc554f-33c9701e4512-1000--delicious-depay-goal-sets-up-psv-victory/ |title=Delicious Depay goal sets up PSV victory |publisher=UEFA |date=3 October 2013 |access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref> Memphis provided the assist for [[Tim Matavž]]'s goal against [[Roda JC Kerkrade|Roda JC]] on 27 October, but picked up two second-half yellow cards and was sent off for the first time in his professional career as PSV lost 2–1.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/10/27/netherlands/eredivisie/roda-jc/psv-nv/1478426/ |title=Roda JC vs. PSV 2–1 |publisher=Soccerway |date=27 October 2013 |access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref> On 15 December, Memphis helped PSV to just their second win in 13 matches, scoring twice in a 5–1 win over [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11913/9075474/eredivisie-psv-beat-utrecht-5-1 |title=Eredivisie: PSV beat Utrecht 5–1 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=15 December 2013 |access-date=18 June 2014}}</ref> Memphis helped PSV rack up their eighth win a row on 23 March 2014, a 3–1 win over Roda JC, having a hand in [[Bryan Ruiz]]'s game-winning goal despite wearing a protective mask to cover a bruised eye socket suffered in a challenge with [[Renato Ibarra]] of [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]] on 15 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://totaldutchfootball.com/2014/03/23/wk29satreport/ |title=Week 29 Eredivisie Report: PSV's winning streak continues |publisher=Total Dutch Football |date=23 March 2014 |access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref>

Memphis helped PSV secure a place in [[UEFA competitions#For clubs|European competition]] for the 41st consecutive year, edging the ball past goalkeeper [[Jelle ten Rouwelaar]] to score their first in a 2–0 win against [[NAC Breda|Breda]]; the final day win ensured that the club would finish fourth in the [[2013–14 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] table.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-finish-fourth-after-20-win-over-NAC.htm |title=PSV finish fourth after 2–0 win over NAC |publisher=PSV |date=3 May 2014 |access-date=18 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505234954/http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-finish-fourth-after-20-win-over-NAC.htm |archive-date=5 May 2014}}</ref>

====2014–15: Top scorer and league title====
After a successful showing at the 2014 World Cup, Memphis was linked to a number of clubs, including [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]<ref>{{cite web |date=24 July 2014 |title=Manchester United monitoring Dutch youngster Memphis Depay ahead of potential deal |url=https://metro.co.uk/2014/07/24/manchester-united-monitoring-dutch-youngster-memphis-depay-ahead-of-potential-deal-4809689/ |access-date=18 August 2014 |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]}}</ref> and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=6 August 2014 |title=Tottenham line up £15m bid for PSV winger Memphis Depay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/06/tottenham-memphis-depay-psv-eindhoven |access-date=18 August 2014 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Amid the speculation surrounding his future, he started the season for PSV in impressive fashion. Memphis came off the bench to score one goal and assist another in the return game of the [[2014–15 UEFA Europa League#Third Qualifying Round|UEFA Europa League]] third qualifying round tie between PSV and [[SKN St. Pölten|St. Pölten]] on 7 August, as his team progressed to the play-off round after a 3–2 away win, giving them a 4–2 aggregate win over the Austrians.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-reach-playoff-round-after-23-win-over-St.-Polten.htm |title=PSV – PSV reach play-off round after 2–3 win over St. Pölten |access-date=18 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812204556/http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-reach-playoff-round-after-23-win-over-St.-Polten.htm |archive-date=12 August 2014}}</ref> In the opening game of the [[2014–15 Eredivisie|Eredivisie season]] three days later, Memphis played a major part in PSV's 3–1 away win against promoted side [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] by scoring two goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-got-off-to-a-flying-start-with-a-13-win-at-Willem-II.htm |title=PSV – PSV got off to a flying start with a 1–3 win at Willem II |access-date=18 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819085214/http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-got-off-to-a-flying-start-with-a-13-win-at-Willem-II.htm |archive-date=19 August 2014}}</ref> He improved on this performance in the following game, scoring two free-kicks and delivering the assist for [[Georginio Wijnaldum]]'s goal in a 6–1 home win against Breda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-hammer-NAC-Breda-61.htm |title=PSV - PSV hammer NAC Breda 6-1 |access-date=18 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820180713/http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/PSV-hammer-NAC-Breda-61.htm |archive-date=20 August 2014}}</ref> On 28 August, in the Europa League play-off second leg away in Belarus, he scored two late goals against [[FC Shakhtyor Soligorsk|Shakhtyor Soligorsk]] as PSV won 3–0 on aggregate to reach the group stage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shakhtyor 0–2 PSV |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2015169--shakhtyor-vs-psv/ |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=28 August 2014 |access-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> Memphis then suffered a groin injury during PSV's 1–3 defeat at [[PEC Zwolle|Zwolle]] on 13 September and he was substituted in the 18th minute.<ref>{{cite news |title=PSV and Netherlands deprived of Depay |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0253-0d7fbe5acd54-99035a933572-1000--psv-and-netherlands-deprived-of-depay/ |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=15 September 2014}}</ref>

On 18 April 2015, Memphis scored PSV's second goal with a free-kick from 35 yards out in a 4–1 home win over Heerenveen to give PSV its 22nd Eredivisie title, its first since 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=PSV 4–1 sc Heerenveen |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32357599|access-date=19 April 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=18 April 2015}}</ref> Later that month, the club confirmed that they had received interest from others wishing to sign him, including Manchester United.<!--DO NOT ADD ANY TEAMS TO THIS SENTENCE WHO ARE NOT NAMED IN THE REFERENCE--><ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay: Man Utd ask after PSV Eindhoven title winner |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32379371 |access-date=21 April 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2015}}</ref> He scored his last home goal for PSV in a 2–0 win against Heracles on 10 May. As he was substituted off he received a standing ovation as well as congratulations from his teammates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32683953 |title=Man Utd signing Depay scores stunner |work=BBC Sport |date=10 May 2015|access-date=12 May 2015}}</ref> He finished the season as the league's top scorer with 22 goals, two ahead of runner-up and teammate [[Luuk de Jong]].<ref name=top>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Doyle |title=Manchester United-bound Depay finishes as Eredivisie's top scorer |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/462/netherlands/2015/05/17/11831712/manchester-united-bound-depay-finishes-as-eredivisies-top |work=Goal.com |date=17 May 2015 |access-date=17 May 2015}}</ref>

===Manchester United===
[[File:Memphis Depay - July 2015c.jpg|250px|thumb|upright|Memphis playing for Manchester United in 2015]]
On 7 May 2015, PSV confirmed that they had agreed a deal with Manchester United over Memphis' transfer, subject to a medical.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfcasia.com/story/2438138/man-united-agree-memphis-depay-deal |title=Memphis Depay's Manchester United move agreed with PSV Eindhoven |work=ESPN |date=7 May 2015 |access-date=7 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32625152 |title=Memphis Depay: Manchester United agree deal for Dutch forward |website=BBC Sport |date=7 May 2015 |access-date=7 May 2015}}</ref> United manager [[Louis van Gaal]] said that he was "forced" into signing him early, due to interest from [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay: Man Utd 'forced' into signing by PSG interest |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32657823|access-date=8 May 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=8 May 2015}}</ref> Though [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] manager [[Brendan Rodgers]] said that he had never been after Memphis, PSV director Marcel Brands stated that he had conversations with Liverpool over a possible transfer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/2445175/liverpool-held-memphis-depay-talks-with-psv-brands |title=Liverpool held Memphis Depay talks with PSV Eindhoven – Marcel Brands |work=ESPN |date=12 May 2015|access-date=12 May 2015}}</ref> On 12 June, United confirmed the signing of Memphis, for a reported fee of £25&nbsp;million on a four-year contract with the option to extend for a further year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Jun/manchester-united-complete-the-signing-of-memphis-depay-from-psv-eindhoven.aspx |title=Manchester United complete the signing of Memphis Depay |publisher=Manchester United |date=12 June 2015|access-date=12 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Memphis Depay completes move to Man Utd from PSV Eindhoven |url=http://www.espnfc.com/manchester-united/story/2488501/memphis-depay-completes-move-to-man-utd |publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|access-date=22 January 2016 |date=12 June 2015}}</ref> He was unveiled as a United player at a press conference on 10 July.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Hibbs |title="Greatest talent" Memphis Depay is first piece in Louis van Gaal's transfer plan |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Jul/Louis-van-Gaal-unveils-Memphis-Depay-and-transfer-plans.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=10 July 2015 |access-date=10 July 2015}}</ref> This made him the fourth player to join United from PSV after [[Jaap Stam]], [[Park Ji-sung]] and [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]]. Memphis made his debut in a pre-season friendly against [[Club América]] in [[Seattle]] on 17 July, contesting the first half as United fielded a different 11 players for each 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hibbs |first=Ben |title=Four new signings shine against Club America |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Jul/New-signings-Schneiderlin-Depay-Darmian-Schweinsteiger-impress-vs-Club-America.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=18 July 2015 |access-date=18 July 2015}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club four days later during a 3–1 win over the [[San Jose Earthquakes]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=Memphis Depay gets off the mark |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Tour-2015/News-and-Features/2015/Jul/memphis-depay-off-the-mark-in-san-jose.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |date=22 July 2015 |access-date=22 July 2015}}</ref> At his own request, after the departure of [[Ángel Di María]], Memphis was given the iconic number 7 shirt – previously worn by former players such as [[George Best]], [[Bryan Robson]], [[Eric Cantona]], [[David Beckham]] and [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Aug/manchester-united-shirt-numbers-for-2015-16-barclays-premier-league.aspx |title=Revealed: Manchester United squad numbers for 2015/16 Barclays Premier League |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=7 August 2015 |access-date=7 August 2015 |first=Adam |last=Marshall}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Rice |title=Memphis Depay wants No 7 shirt that Angel Di Maria is vacating at Manchester United |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/memphis-depay-wants-no-7-shirt-that-angel-di-maria-is-vacating-at-manchester-united-10442348.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220512/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/memphis-depay-wants-no-7-shirt-that-angel-di-maria-is-vacating-at-manchester-united-10442348.html |archive-date=12 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print |date=6 August 2015 |access-date=7 August 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Cskamu 52.jpg|thumb|left|Memphis during a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in 2015]]

Memphis made his [[Premier League]] debut on 8 August as the season opened with a 1–0 victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[Old Trafford]]. He was substituted after 68 minutes for [[Ander Herrera]], and Van Gaal said after the match that Memphis was playing in too eager a manner.<ref>{{cite news |last=Magowan |first=Alistair |date=8 August 2015 |title=Manchester United 1–0 Tottenham Hotspur |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33744640 |access-date=8 August 2015 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 18 August, Memphis scored his first two goals for Manchester United, and assisted [[Maroune Fellaini]]'s final goal, in a 3–1 home victory over [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]] in the first leg of the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round|Champions League play-offs]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd 3–1 Club Brugge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33954080 |work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=18 August 2015 |date=18 August 2015}}</ref> In the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round|second leg]], Memphis provided the assist for the first of [[Wayne Rooney]]'s three goals. He scored again on 15 September in the first game of the competition's [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]], in an eventual 2–1 loss at his former team PSV.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magowan |first1=Alistair |title=PSV 2–1 Man Utd |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34203615|access-date=16 September 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=15 September 2015}}</ref> Memphis scored his first league goal on 26 September, opening a 3–0 home win over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], a victory that put United on top of the league for the first time in 110 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd 3–0 Sunderland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34299545|access-date=26 September 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Richardson |first=James |last2=Green |first2=Ben |date=28 September 2015 |title=Football Weekly: Manchester United top the table as City slump at Spurs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2015/sep/28/football-weekly-podcast-manchester-united-top-man-city-slump |access-date=4 October 2015 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Following his early struggles in the Premier League, Memphis told Dutch newspaper ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', "There are a lot of games in Manchester. There are very few rest days and on training days you are mainly concerned with recovering. It's heavy, two games a week, always at a high level, and my body has to get used to that". These claims were dismissed by assistant manager and former United player [[Ryan Giggs]], who blamed Memphis' flashy lifestyle for his poor form.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/manchester-united-winger-memphis-depay-6610204 |title=Manchester United winger Memphis Depay warned over lifestyle by Ryan Giggs after Emirates shocker |work=Daily Mirror |date=11 October 2015 |access-date=18 October 2015}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=tabloid|date=June 2022}} Memphis was later dropped to the bench, along with countryman [[Daley Blind]], during United's 3–0 win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 17 October, following the Netherlands' failure to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34493717 |title=Everton 0–3 Man Utd |work=BBC Sport |date=17 October 2015 |access-date=18 October 2015}}</ref> Despite this, Memphis was named in the 59-man longlist for the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or]], but did not make the shortlist.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ballon d'Or shortlist: Eight Manchester-based players in running for award |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ballon-dor-list-leaked-fifa-10180903 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=2 October 2015|access-date=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester United trio miss out on Ballon D'Or shortlist |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-trio-miss-out-10293671 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=20 October 2015|access-date=21 October 2015}}</ref>

After being dropped in four consecutive matches, Memphis got his first start as a second striker due to [[Anthony Martial]] and Rooney's unavailability, and seized the opportunity with his second league goal in a 2–1 away win over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] at [[Vicarage Road]]. His performance earned praise from van Gaal, as well as his first Premier League Man of the Match honour.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Louis van Gaal hails Memphis Depay after Manchester United victory |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/10074157/louis-van-gaal-hails-very-good-memphis-depay-performance |work=Sky Sports|access-date=22 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Scott |date=21 November 2015 |title=Watford v Manchester United: Premier League – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/nov/21/watford-v-manchester-united-premier-league-live-updates |access-date=22 November 2015 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[File:OL-MHSC (2017) - Memphis Depay.jpg|thumb|upright|Memphis playing for Lyon in 2017]] In February, Memphis scored in each of United's [[2015–16 UEFA Europa League|two Europa League matches]] against [[FC Midtjylland|Midtjylland]] as they won 6–3 on aggregate; Memphis was lauded for his performance in the home leg, where he not only scored but also set up the first goal, earned his side two penalties and delivered a cross that led to an own goal. Van Gaal hailed the match as a "turning point" for Memphis.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Alex |last=Richards |title=Louis van Gaal hails Memphis Depay "turning point" – and PRAISES Anthony Martial |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/louis-van-gaal-hails-memphis-7444836 |website=Daily Mirror |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=26 February 2016}}</ref>

Memphis made only four appearances (all of them as a substitute) and had a total playing time of just 20 minutes in the Premier League during the [[2016–17 Premier League|2016–17 season]]. He only started one match in the season – the [[2016–17 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] third round 3–1 away win over League One club [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on 21 September 2016 – and was substituted after playing 55 minutes of that match. Following this, he played only 46 minutes, and his last match for the club was on 24 November, when he played the final eight minutes of a 4–0 [[2016–17 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League]] home victory against [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United worried Memphis Depay will stay at Old Trafford |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/manchester-united-worried-memphis-depay-will-stay-old-trafford-1601545 |newspaper=International Business Times |date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay bid not reasonable – Man United manager Jose Mourinho |url=http://www.espnfc.com/manchester-united/story/3037729/memphis-depay-bid-not-reasonable-man-united-manager-jose-mourinho |publisher=ESPN FC |date=13 January 2017}}</ref>

===Lyon===
On 20 January 2017, Memphis signed a four-and-a-half-year deal with French club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] which would keep him at the French club until the summer of 2021. The initial transfer fee was estimated to be £16–17&nbsp;million, potentially rising to £22&nbsp;million with the add-ons including Lyon qualifying for the [[UEFA Champions League]] and Memphis earning a new contract. The terms of the deal also included buy-back and sell-on clauses for United.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/club/netherlands/449/blog/post/3868110/how-memphis-depay-overcame-a-nightmare-childhood-and-failure-at-man-united-to-become-the-netherlands-star-forward |title=How Memphis Depay overcame a nightmare childhood and failure at Man United to become the Netherlands' star forward |last=Kuper |first=Simon |date=5 June 2019 |website=ESPN|access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United: Memphis Depay makes move to Lyon |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38663810 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=21 January 2017}}</ref> Two days later, he made his debut for Lyon, coming on as substitute for [[Mathieu Valbuena]] in the 79th minute in a home [[Ligue 1]] match against [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], which Lyon won 3–1.<ref>{{cite news |date=23 January 2017 |title=OL-OM: Le nom de Mathieu Valbuena scandé à Lyon... "Comme quoi, tout peut arriver", sourit-il |url=https://fr.sports.yahoo.com/news/ol-om-nom-mathieu-valbuena-234906844.html |publisher=Yahoo(France) Sports}}{{dead link|date=February 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> On 28 January, he made his first start for Lyon in a 2–1 league defeat to [[Lille OSC|Lille]], and was substituted in the 68th minute by [[Maxwel Cornet]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzia brace knocks back OL |url=http://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/benzia-brace-knocks-back-ol.htm |publisher=ligue1.com |date=28 January 2017}}</ref> On 12 March in a game against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]], Memphis scored a goal from close to the halfway line. He later said it was "the goal of my life", although he also distanced himself from comparisons to [[David Beckham]]'s famous halfway line goal against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/lyon/story/3081389/lyons-memphis-depay-on-goal-from-halfway-line-im-not-david-beckham |title=Lyon's Memphis Depay on goal from halfway line: 'I'm not David Beckham' |last=Holyman |first=Ian |date=13 March 2017|access-date=13 March 2017 |publisher=[[ESPN FC]]}}</ref>

On the final day of the [[2017–18 Ligue 1|2017–18 season]], Memphis scored a hat-trick against [[OGC Nice|Nice]] as Lyon won 3–2 and qualified for the Champions League.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ligue 1: Memphis Depay's hat trick puts Lyon in Champions League; Troyes relegated |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/french-ligue-1/story/3504434/ligue-1-memphis-depays-hat-trick-puts-lyon-in-champions-league-troyes-relegated |work=PA Sports |publisher=[[ESPN FC]] |date=19 May 2018|access-date=21 May 2018}}</ref>

On 5 November 2019, Memphis scored his fourth goal in as many games for Lyon against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in a 3–1 win in the [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League|2019–20 Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/us/uefa-champions-league/news/memphis-depay-shines-as-lyon-sink-benfica/1338530 |title=Depay Extends Champions League Goal Streak as Lyon Sink Benfica |website=beIN SPORTS |date=5 November 2019}}</ref> On 10 December, he scored an equaliser against [[RB Leipzig]] in a 2–2 draw to help Lyon to qualify to the knockout phase, hence he scored in five consecutive matches in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |date=10 December 2019 |title=Ligue des champions : Memphis envoie Lyon au paradis... et s'emporte contre certains supporters |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/football/ligue-des-champions-memphis-envoie-lyon-au-paradis-10-12-2019-8214669.php |website=Le Parisien |language=fr}}</ref> On 15 December, Memphis tore his anterior cruciate ligament while playing against Rennes in Ligue 1, ending a successful season during which he had scored nine goals in 12 league starts for Lyon.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11887996/netherlands-memphis-depay-set-to-miss-euro-2020-after-rupturing-acl |title=Netherlands' Memphis Depay set to miss Euro 2020 after rupturing ACL |website=Sky Sports|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref> He returned from his injury to start for Lyon in their 5–6 penalty shootout loss in the [[2020 Coupe de la Ligue Final|French league cup final]] against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] on 31 July 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |title=MATCHDAY: PSG can do the treble with League Cup win vs. Lyon |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2020/07/30/matchday-psg-can-do-the-treble-with-league-cup-win-vs-lyon/41987771/|access-date=4 August 2020 |website=USA Today}}</ref> [[File:Memphis Depay Barca 2021.jpg|180px|thumb|Memphis playing for Barcelona in 2021]]
On 7 August, Memphis scored in his sixth consecutive Champions League match, converting a penalty in a 2–1 loss to [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] in the second leg of their round of 16 tie; he is only the second Dutch player to score in six straight Champions League games, following former Manchester United striker [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]]. The tie finished 2–2 on aggregate, but Lyon progressed on the away goals rule.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53683503 |title=Juventus 2–1 Lyon |website=BBC Sport |date=7 August 2020}}</ref> Lyon eventually reached the semi-finals for the second time in their history since 2010 after defeating [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].

On 28 August 2020, Memphis scored a hat-trick in a 4–1 win against [[Dijon FCO|Dijon]], in the first match of the 2020–21 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.givemesport.com/1595303-memphis-depay-scores-hattrick-for-lyon-and-then-suggests-hes-leaving-the-club |title=Memphis Depay scores hat-trick for Lyon and then suggests he's leaving the club |website=GiveMeSport |date=29 August 2020}}</ref>

===Barcelona===
On 19 June 2021, [[La Liga]] club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] announced the free transfer of Memphis on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/2174668/memphis-depay-barcas-fourth-signing |title=Memphis Depay Barça's fourth signing |website=FC Barcelona |date=19 June 2021}}</ref> According to his grandmother, since the age of four, he had been aspiring to be a player for Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vlietstra |first=Bart |date=4 June 2021 |title=Memphis Depay: how Netherlands' troubled teen became a Dutch icon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/04/memphis-depay-how-netherlands-troubled-teen-became-a-dutch-icon |access-date=19 June 2021 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 15 August, Memphis made his Barcelona debut in a 4–2 league victory against [[Real Sociedad]] at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/2220661/fc-barcelona-4-2-real-sociedad-camp-nou-celebrates-a-winning-start |title=FC Barcelona 4-2 Real Sociedad: Camp Nou celebrates a winning start |website=[[FC Barcelona]] |date=15 August 2021 |accessdate=22 August 2021}}</ref> Six days later, he scored his first goal for the club in his second match when he scored the equaliser against [[Athletic Bilbao]] in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/2227595/memphis-scores-first-official-goal |title=Memphis scores first official goal |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |date=21 August 2021|access-date=22 August 2021}}</ref>

=== Atlético Madrid ===
On 20 January 2023, [[Atlético Madrid]] announced the signing of Memphis on a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Club Atlético de Madrid - Welcome, Memphis! |url=https://en.atleticodemadrid.com/noticias/welcome-memphis |access-date=2023-01-20 |website=Club Atlético de Madrid |date=20 January 2023 |language=en}}</ref> The initial transfer fee was estimated to be over €4 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-20 |title=Atleti complete signing of Memphis from Barca |url=https://www.espn.in/football/soccer-transfers/story/4855682/memphis-joins-atletico-from-barcelona-in-4m-deal |access-date=2023-01-20 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> On 12 February, he scored his first goal in a 1–0 away victory over [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.atleticodemadrid.com/noticias/memphis-signs-the-victory-in-balaidos |title=Memphis signs the victory in Balaídos |publisher=Atlético de Madrid |date=12 February 2023 }}</ref> On 13 March 2024, Memphis scored the winning goal in the 87th minute in a 2–1 victory over [[Inter Milan]] in the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]] second leg, which tied the encounter at 2–2 on aggregate; however, Atlético would later win 3–2 on penalties to advance to the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/sport/20240313-atletico-beat-inter-on-penalties-to-reach-champions-league-quarters |title=Atletico beat Inter on penalties to reach Champions League quarters |publisher=France 24 |date=14 March 2024 }}</ref> On 22 May 2024, Memphis Depay and Atlético de Madrid agreed to part ways.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://x.com/fabrizioromano/status/1793250502630613161?s=46|title=Depay terminates Atlético contract|publisher=Fabrizio Romano|date=22 May 2024}}</ref>

=== Corinthians ===
On 9 September 2024, Brazilian side [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] announced the signing of Memphis on a two-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 September 2024 |title=Memphis Depay é o novo atacante do Corinthians |url=https://www.corinthians.com.br/noticias/memphis-depay-e-o-novo-atacante-do-corinthians |access-date=10 September 2024 |publisher=Sport Club Corinthians Paulista |language=pt}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 18 October 2024 against [[Club Athletico Paranaense|Athletico Paranaense]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/serie-a-brazil/articles-video/-video-memphis-depay-s-first-goal-with-corinthians-is-insane-2024-10-18|title=(Video) Memphis Depay's First Goal with Corinthians is Insane!|date=18 October 2024|website=beIN SPORTS|accessdate=18 October 2024}}</ref> On 4 December, he scored twice, which included a free-kick, and assisted [[Yuri Alberto]], as Corinthians beat [[Esporte Clube Bahia|Bahia]] 3–0.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-12-04 |title=Sensational Memphis free-kick steals the show as Corinthians beat Bahia 3-0 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/sensational-memphis-free-kick-steals-113100404.html |access-date=2024-12-12 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> That season, Memphis decisively helped a struggling Corinthians side avoid relegation in the [[2024 Campeonato Brasileiro Série A|Brasileirão]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-10-29 |title=Memphis assume protagonismo e vira arma do Corinthians para salvar 2024 |url=https://ge.globo.com/futebol/times/corinthians/noticia/2024/10/29/memphis-assume-protagonismo-e-vira-arma-do-corinthians-para-salvar-2024.ghtml |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=ge |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-11-12 |title=Fator Memphis: aproveitamento do Corinthians com o holandês é melhor do que o do líder Botafogo |url=https://ge.globo.com/futebol/times/corinthians/noticia/2024/11/12/fator-memphis-aproveitamento-do-corinthians-com-o-holandes-e-melhor-do-que-o-do-lider-botafogo.ghtml |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=ge |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-12-01 |title=TV dos Países Baixos coloca Memphis Depay como o ‘salvador’ e faz análise do Corinthians em 2024 |url=https://www.meutimao.com.br/noticias-do-corinthians/494379/tv-dos-paises-baixos-coloca-memphis-depay-como-o-salvador-e-faz-analise-do-corinthians-em-2024 |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=Meu Timão |language=pt-br}}</ref>

On 16 March 2025, Memphis assisted [[Yuri Alberto]] in a 1–0 away victory over [[SE Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] in the [[Campeonato Paulista|Paulista Championship]] final, helping the team secure the title and end a six-year long trophy drought.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-03-16 |title=Corinthians: assistência de Memphis na final rende "bolada" ao camisa 10 |url=https://www.cnnbrasil.com.br/esportes/futebol/corinthians/corinthians-assistencia-de-memphis-na-final-rende-bolada-ao-camisa-10/ |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=CNN Brasil |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-11-01 |title=OPINIÃO: Eliminado, endividado e em fila recorde, Corinthians vive pior fase do século no ano do 'fim da farra' |url=https://www.espn.com.br/futebol/corinthians/artigo/_/id/14387973/opiniao-eliminado-endividado-fila-recorde-corinthians-vive-pior-fase-seculo-ano-fim-farra |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=ESPN.com |language=pt}}</ref>

On 30 July, Memphis scored against rivals [[SE Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] in the first leg of [[2025 Copa do Brasil|Copa do Brasil]] round of 16. On 10 December, he scored against the record winner [[Cruzeiro EC|Cruzeiro]], helping Corinthians advance to the Copa do Brasil final, which was played against [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Cruzeiro 0 x 1 Corinthians {{!}} Copa do Brasil: melhores momentos |url=https://ge.globo.com/mg/futebol/copa-do-brasil/jogo/10-12-2025/cruzeiro-corinthians.ghtml |access-date=2025-12-17 |website=ge |language=pt-br}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-12-16 |title=CBF antecipa segundo jogo da final da Copa do Brasil; veja novo horário |url=https://www.cnnbrasil.com.br/esportes/futebol/copa-do-brasil/cbf-antecipa-segundo-jogo-da-final-da-copa-do-brasil-veja-novo-horario/ |access-date=2025-12-17 |website=CNN Brasil |language=pt-BR}}</ref> After a scoreless home draw, Corinthians went on to face Vasco at the [[Maracanã Stadium|Maracanã]], defeating them 2–1, with a goal by Memphis, and won the title for the fourth time in club history.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-12-21 |title=Yuri e Memphis decidem, Corinthians bate Vasco e conquista a Copa do Brasil |url=https://www.uol.com.br/esporte/futebol/ultimas-noticias/2025/12/21/vasco-corinthians-final-copa-do-brasil.htm |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=UOL |language=pt-br}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Silva |first=Cleverton |date=2025-12-21 |title=É tetra! Corinthians bate Vasco e conquista título da Copa do Brasil |url=https://www.metropoles.com/esportes/vasco-e-corinthians-decidem-o-titulo-da-copa-do-brasil-acompanhe |access-date=2025-12-22 |website=www.metropoles.com |language=pt-BR}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Memphis played youth international football for the Netherlands at under-15,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/185192/uitslagen |title=Jeugd mannen onder 15 Uitslagen |website=onsoranje.nl |access-date=28 November 2022}}</ref> under-16,<ref>{{cite web |title=Memphis Depay Jeugd mannen onder 16 |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/185191/speler/102 |access-date=28 November 2022 |website=onsoranje.nl}}</ref> [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|under-17]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/184965/speler/102 |title=Memphis Depay Jeugd mannen onder 17 |website=onsoranje.nl |access-date=28 November 2022}}</ref> [[Netherlands national under-19 football team|under-19]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/185189/speler/102 |title=Memphis Depay Jeugd mannen onder 19 |website=onsoranje.nl |access-date=28 November 2022}}</ref> and [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/185185/speler/102 |title=Memphis Depay Jong Oranje |website=onsoranje.nl |access-date=28 November 2022}}</ref> He was a member of the under-17 team which won the [[2011 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2011 European Championship]] in Serbia. In the final against [[Germany national under-17 football team|Germany]] in [[Novi Sad]], he scored the goal which put the Netherlands ahead as they came from behind to defeat [[Germany–Netherlands football rivalry|their rivals]] 5–2.<ref name=under/> Later that year, he participated in the [[2011 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] held in Mexico.

===Senior===
{{See also|List of international goals scored by Memphis Depay}}
Memphis made his international debut on 15 October 2013, coming on for [[Jeremain Lens]] in the last minute of a 2–0 away win against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] at the [[Şükrü Saracoğlu Stadium]] in [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Türker |last=Tozar |title=Dutch double ends Turkey hopes |url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/matches/round=2000294/match=2008632/postmatch/report/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115062106/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/matches/round=2000294/match=2008632/postmatch/report/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 November 2015 |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=15 October 2013 |access-date=26 April 2015}}</ref> Memphis was selected by Netherlands manager Louis van Gaal in the final 23-man squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news |title=Van Gaal names Netherlands World Cup squad |url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2112545.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140603040509/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2112545.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 June 2014 |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=31 May 2014 |access-date=18 June 2014}}</ref> He came on as a substitute before the half-time whistle in the second group match against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] to replace defender [[Bruno Martins Indi]], who had sustained a head injury, and in the 68th minute he scored the winning goal, a swerving effort from outside the box. He also set up [[Robin van Persie]]'s equaliser.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oranje Edge Five Goal Thriller |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=oranje-edge-five-goal-thriller-2375665.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620132913/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=oranje-edge-five-goal-thriller-2375665.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 June 2014 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association |date=18 June 2014 |access-date=18 June 2014}}</ref> He became the youngest Dutchman to score a goal at the World Cup, at the age of 20 years and four months.<ref name="test2">{{cite news |title=Memphis the hero for Oranje |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=memphis-el-heroe-naranja-2376893-2376934.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622020238/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=memphis-el-heroe-naranja-2376893-2376934.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 June 2014 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association |date=19 June 2014 |access-date=26 July 2015}}</ref> He came on as a substitute again in the final group match against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 23 June in [[São Paulo]] and scored the second goal for the Dutch, tapping in an [[Arjen Robben]] cross, as they clinched first place with a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Woodcock |title=Netherlands 2–0 Chile |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25285270 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=23 June 2014 |access-date=26 July 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Depay NL Training 2015.jpg|thumb|Memphis training with the Netherlands in March 2015]]
On 11 July, Memphis was named on the three-man shortlist for the tournament's [[2014 FIFA World Cup#Awards|Best Young Player]] award, together with Frenchmen [[Paul Pogba]] and [[Raphaël Varane]],<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2014: Fifa announces Golden Ball shortlist |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28274011 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=11 July 2014 |access-date=12 July 2014}}</ref> but lost out to Pogba.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pogba wins Hyundai Young Player Award |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=pogba-wins-hyundai-young-player-award-2405061.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714130631/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=pogba-wins-hyundai-young-player-award-2405061.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 July 2014 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association |date=13 July 2014 |access-date=26 July 2015}}</ref>

Memphis' first goal since the World Cup came in a friendly at the [[Amsterdam Arena]] on 5 June 2015, deflecting [[Klaas-Jan Huntelaar]]'s shot to put the Netherlands 3–1 up against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], although the team eventually lost 4–3.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Tim |date=5 June 2015 |title=Holland 3–4 USA – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/jun/05/holland-usa-soccer-international-friendly-live |access-date=5 June 2015 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In October of that year, he was involved in a fight with teammate Robin van Persie at an international training camp; manager [[Danny Blind]] stated to the media, "There are sometimes situations in training where players think different. Then you talk about it. That's what happened and then it's over."<ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay and Robin van Persie in training ground bust-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34510525|access-date=13 October 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=12 October 2015}}</ref> The following month, both Memphis and Van Persie were dropped from the Dutch squad for friendlies against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Germany national football team|Germany]], with Blind stating of Memphis, "In football you must function in a team. He doesn't always do that. That's something he has to learn."<ref>{{cite news |title=Netherlands drop Memphis Depay and Robin van Persie for Wales |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34700893|access-date=4 November 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2015}}</ref>

Memphis was among the final 26 players selected by coach [[Frank de Boer]] to represent Netherlands in [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]]. He scored twice in four matches as Netherlands were eliminated in the round of 16 stage by [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024480--netherlands-vs-czech-republic/postmatch/report/ |title=Netherlands 0-2 Czech Republic: Czechs shock Dutch to reach quarters |website=[[UEFA]] |date=27 June 2021 |accessdate=13 August 2021}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

On 7 September 2021, Memphis scored his first international hat-trick in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group G|2022 World Cup qualification]] 6–1 win over [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], reaching 33 goals and equaling [[Johan Cruyff]]'s and [[Abe Lenstra]]'s goalscoring tallies for the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/memphis-scores-first-netherlands-hat-trick-to-level-cruyff/h2y9rtiaf9s1ni18olhgk3t3 |title=Memphis scores first Netherlands hat-trick to level Cruyff in all-time scoring chart |website=[[Goal.com]] |date=7 September 2021 |accessdate=7 September 2021}}</ref>

Memphis scored a last-minute winner against Wales on 14 June 2022 in the [[UEFA Nations League]], taking him to 42 international goals, level with [[Klaas-Jan Huntelaar]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Blanche |title=Memphis Depay ensures Holland deny Wales at the death again |url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/memphis-depay-ensures-holland-deny-205307274.html |website=Yahoo! Sport |date=14 June 2022 |accessdate=12 July 2022}}</ref>

In November 2022, he was named in the Dutch squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/nieuws/nederlands-elftal/80525/van-gaal-maakt-26-koppige-wk-selectie-bekend |title=Van Gaal maakt 26-koppige WK-selectie bekend |trans-title=Van Gaal announces 26-man World Cup squad |publisher=[[Royal Dutch Football Association]] |date=11 November 2022 |access-date=12 November 2022 |language=nl}}</ref> On 3 December, he scored a goal in a 3–1 win over the United States in the round of 16, to become the second all-time top scorer for his country with 43 goals, behind [[Robin van Persie]]'s 50.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/memphis-netherlands-difference-maker-usa-fifa-world-cup-qatar-2022 |title=Memphis Depay – Netherlands' difference maker? |publisher=FIFA |date=3 December 2022 }}</ref>

On 29 May 2024, Memphis was named in the Netherlands' squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Callum |date=29 May 2024 |title=Netherlands Euro 2024 squad: Georginio Wijnaldum and Daley Blind retained |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5526712/2024/05/29/netherlands-euro-2024-squad-confirmed/ |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 23 March 2025, he played his 100th international match for the Netherlands, scoring a goal in a 3–3 away draw against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] during the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League A|Nations League quarter-finals]], which ultimately ended in a defeat on penalties.<ref>{{cite web |date=23 March 2025 |title=Jubilaris Memphis Depay kruipt met goal tegen Spanje weer wat dichter naar Oranje-topscorer Robin van Persie toe |url=https://www.ad.nl/voetbal/jubilaris-memphis-depay-kruipt-met-goal-tegen-spanje-weer-wat-dichter-naar-oranje-topscorer-robin-van-persie-toe~a88fbdf6/ |publisher=AD.nl |language=nl}}</ref>

On 10 June 2025, in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group G|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification game]] against [[Malta national football team|Malta]], he scored his 49th and 50th international goals, to become joint top goalscorer of Netherlands with [[Robin van Persie]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay matches record for the Netherlands |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/memphis-depay-matches-record-netherlands-191800940.html |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=10 June 2025}}</ref> He made the record his own when he opened the scoring against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 7 September, taking him to 51 goals for Oranje. He then scored the winning goal as the Netherlands won 3–2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c1dxd1zn1wvt|title=Lithuania 2-3 Netherlands: Memphis Depay scores 51st international goal to become record scorer for Dutch|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> "I'm super proud and very glad I got past Robin. I thanked everyone in the dressing room," he told [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]]. "I also want to thank old teammates like Klaas-Jan Huntelaar and Arjen Robben, for example. They inspired me. The same goes for [[Patrick Kluivert]]. It was because of him that I wanted to reach the Dutch national team."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/depay-proud-breaking-dutch-record-2025-09-07/ |title=Depay proud of breaking Dutch record |publisher=Reuters |date=7 September 2025 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
[[File:Memphis Depay.jpg|thumb|Memphis playing for PSV Eindhoven in 2011]]
Early in his career, a PSV coach noted Memphis as "very angry", and he now uses a [[life coach]] to aid his mentality.<ref name=things/> In April 2015, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Memphis as "a fearsome striker of the ball with his right foot but is usually used as an [[Inverted Winger|inverted left winger]] who cuts onto his right foot. A pacey and tricky player, his direct running makes him a difficult opponent for defenders".<ref name=things/> However, they criticised him as "a ball-hog", pointing out his high rate of shots in comparison to a low rate of assists.<ref name=things/> Memphis is also known for his [[Direct free kick|free-kick ability]]. During the 2014–15 season, he was statistically the best set-piece taker in the whole of Europe, as he scored 7 times in 33 attempts, the most in all European leagues and the second-best accuracy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Man United's Memphis Depay is statistically the best free kick taker in Europe |url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/man-uniteds-memphis-depay-is-statistically-the-best-free-kick-taker-in-europe-graphics/ |publisher=101 Great Goals|access-date=4 October 2015|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304100851/http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/man-uniteds-memphis-depay-is-statistically-the-best-free-kick-taker-in-europe-graphics/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=This stat proves Man United's new transfer signing Depay will RULE the Prem&nbsp;... |url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/05/11/manchester-united-signing-memphis-depay-is-the-best-free-kick-taker-in-europe-5191906/ |website=Metro|access-date=4 October 2015 |first=Tom |last=Olver |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Memphis Depay's Free Kick Stats Make Great Reading For Man United Fans |website=Balls.ie |url=http://www.balls.ie/football/00910-memphis-depay-free-kick-stats-man-united-fans/288223 |access-date=4 October 2015 |first=Mikey |last=Traynor|date=11 May 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=A nice little stat to get Manchester United fans excited about Memphis Depay |website=SportsJOE.ie |url=http://www.sportsjoe.ie/football/a-nice-little-stat-to-get-manchester-united-fans-excited-about-memphis-depay/24212 |access-date=4 October 2015 |archive-date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720100644/http://www.sportsjoe.ie/football/a-nice-little-stat-to-get-manchester-united-fans-excited-about-memphis-depay/24212 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Former Dutch international and Dutch national team manager [[Ronald Koeman]] regards Memphis as "a great talent", but says that he must continue his personal development due to the physicality and mental strength needed in the Premier League.<ref name="bbc" /> Former [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] defender [[Arjan de Zeeuw]] stated about Memphis: "People regard him as a little bit arrogant, a little bit cocky, but I think he is a very good player, a very promising player, a very strong, very quick player and he's got some skill."<ref name="bbc" />

Memphis has been compared to former Manchester United player [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and fellow international [[Arjen Robben]]. Thijs Slegers said about the comparisons: "Memphis is a little bit like Cristiano; they have similar qualities, although there are of course areas where Memphis is inferior. However, his determination to be the best is where I see the real similarity with Cristiano."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manchester United winger Memphis Depay is 'more like Ronaldo than Robben' |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=9 June 2015 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/manchester-united-winger-memphis-depay-5854102|access-date=4 October 2015}}</ref> Like Ronaldo, he combines technical expertise with pure physical strength.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Memphis Depay is a huge talent – but would he suit Liverpool or Man United more? |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/scouting-report-memphis-depay-huge-5557697|access-date=4 October 2015 |first=Elko |last=Born |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=21 April 2015}}</ref>

==Musical career==
Memphis began pursuing a hip-hop career in June 2017 when he released his Los Angeles-inspired freestyle, "LA Vibes". The music video featured [[Quincy Promes]], Memphis' teammate at the Netherlands national team. The song's music video earned around 150,000 views within hours of being uploaded to [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Footballer Memphis Depay releases rap song |date=27 June 2017 |url=http://www.egypttoday.com/Article/8/9036/Footballer-Memphis-Depay-releases-rap-song |publisher=Egypt Today|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref> In December 2017, Memphis released his freestyle track "Kings & Queens". On 3 October 2018, he collaborated with musical artists [[Winne]] and Nana Fofie and producer Rass King for his Ghana-inspired single, "AKWAABA",<ref>{{cite web |last=Macaluso |first=Massimiliano |title=Memphis Depay, Rapper and Philanthropist |work=NSS Magazine |publisher=NSS Factory |url=http://www.nssmag.com/en/sports/16333/la-nuova-vita-extracalcistica-di-memphis-depay}}</ref> and also released his third freestyle, "Porto Cervo (Interlude)", with Winne. Memphis released his fourth freestyle, "5-mill" in response to his [[Instagram]] account reaching 5&nbsp;million followers. Critics of the freestyle claimed that Memphis' public image was hampered through his cigar-smoking and his careless attitude.<ref>{{cite news |title=Memphis Depay's rap video met with praise and bewilderment online |url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/and-finally/memphis-depays-rap-video-met-with-praise-and-bewilderment-online-37563995.html |newspaper=The Independent|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>

In December 2018, he released his second single, "No Love", over his cancelled engagement with model [[Lori Harvey]]. The song is multilingual, switching back and forth between English and Dutch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/188969-lori-harveys-ex-fianc-drops-music-video-with-no-love-subliminals-news |title=Lori Harvey's Ex-Fiancé Drops Music Video With "No Love" Subliminals |website=hotnewhiphop.com |date=31 December 2018|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>

In July 2019, Memphis released "Fall Back".<ref>{{Citation |title=Memphis Depay - Fall Back (Official Video) | date=21 July 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sk6zkOc9SKY |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> On 1 November 2019, [[Broederliefde]] released an album, ''Broeders'', which featured Memphis in the song "Lange Jas".<ref>{{Citation |title=Lange Jas | date=12 December 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RWyoj9WmVY0 |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> On 17 April 2020, he released "Dubai Freestyle".

In September 2020, Memphis released his new song "2 Corinthians 5:7".<ref>{{Citation |title=Memphis Depay - 2 Corinthians 5:7 (Official Video) | date=2 September 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xjtNp-RStOs |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> A month later on October 9, 2020, Memphis released "Blessing".<ref>{{Citation |title=Memphis Depay - Blessing (Official Video) | date=9 October 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oss23JNZ3q4 |access-date=2023-06-18 |language=en}}</ref> The song's music video shows Memphis returning to his home town of [[Moordrecht]]. Memphis wrote a passage in his autobiography ''Heart of a Lion'', which explained the meaning of the song.

"I wrote a track about this, called ''Blessings'', and it includes these lines:<blockquote>''Seems like everybody’s wishing for the same shit.''

''They want a [[Rolex|Roley]] and a chain, oh yeah''

''The other type of n*ggas that complain, ah''

''Keep waiting for a blessing but forget to pray, ah yeah''</blockquote>The point I'm making here is that young people wish for all sorts of things, but often forget to pray for them. Purely material success is often very empty. I know millionaires who are deeply unhappy, while the outside world thinks they're successful and everything’s just perfect for them. I’ve learned that appearances can be deceptive. Being special in your own way: that’s true success."<ref>{{Cite book |last=Depay; Zwartkruis |first=Memphis; Simon |title=Heart of a Lion |year=2019 |location=Amsterdam |pages=130 |language=nl, en}}</ref>

On 27 November 2020, he released his debut album ''Heavy Stepper''. A 9 track EP including "2 Corinthians 5:7" and "Blessing" released as singles shortly before, and new tracks "Heavy Stepper", "Body Like You (feat. Zah Santori)", "From Ghana (feat. Rass King & Bisa Kdei)", "4AM Palm Flow", "Big Fish", the highly anticipated "For A Week" and "D.B.A (feat. [[Yasmin Lauryn]])".<ref>{{Citation |title=Heavy Stepper |date=2020-11-27 |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6GUlB3T4rAWUg0bDVRoFiO |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref>

In 2021, he appeared on 101Barz<ref>{{Citation |title=MEMPHIS DEPAY {{!}} Studiosessie 387 {{!}} 101Barz | date=21 September 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NM50jb2mtOE |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> performing two freestyles. In 2022, he became more active, collaborating with SFB and [[Quincy Promes]] in the track "TAT TAT",<ref>{{Citation |title=SFB - TAT TAT ft. Memphis Depay & Quincy Promes (prod. LYNCH) | date=11 November 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cI6iC5w5pgg |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> which was released in November 2022. In January 2023, he collaborated with [[Bisa Kdei]] on an [[Afrobeat|afro-beat]] track "Drinks on Me".<ref>{{Citation |title=Drinks On Me | date=19 January 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVxOmfXja-8 |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> This followed two more releases so far in 2023 including "Asem Beba"<ref>{{Citation |title=Memphis Depay - Asem Beba | date=13 February 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2D2q_Sp9vmo |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> in February and "Leven Als Een Prof",<ref>{{Citation |title=Memphis Depay - Leven Als Een Prof | date=28 April 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WB3n8bGBpDk |access-date=2023-06-16 |language=en}}</ref> translating to 'life as a professional', in April. In July 2023, Memphis released his third release of the year with the track "These Days", another multi-lingual track which switches between the Dutch and English language.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-01 |title=Memphis Depay: 5 Essential songs from the Atletico Madrid star you need to listen to |url=https://www.pulsesports.ng/story/memphis-depay-essential-songs-you-need-to-listen-to-2023080113143049035 |access-date=2026-04-10 |website=Pulse Sports Nigeria |language=en}}</ref> In October 2023, Memphis released "Baby Don't Play", an all English afro-beat track in a style which is inspired by his Ghanaian roots.

Memphis has a lot of unreleased music which can be found on YouTube,<ref>{{Citation |title=MEMPHIS DEPAY UNRELEASED SONGS COMPILATION [2023] | date=13 October 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Hmt9seVwpI |access-date=2023-06-17 |language=en}}</ref> clipped from Instagram stories or live streams between 2018 and 2022. Memphis claims he plans to release when it is the "right time".

